        "content": "<p>I am wondering if there is terminology to distinguish between what something is defined “in terms of” or “with reference to”, vs. what something <em>is</em>.</p>\n<p>For example, a cone is defined “with reference to” a diagram. That is why it is technically called, say, “a cone of a functor”, or, “a cone over a diagram”. We cannot define a cone without a specifying a diagram. It exists in relation to it.</p>\n<p>A cone also requires the specification of an object, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span>. For some functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>J</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F: J \\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> and for an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N \\in C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7224em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, a cone “from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>” is <em>a family of morphisms</em>.</p>\n<p>So a cone requires an object and a functor to be defined, but “<em>what it is</em>” is a <em>family of morphisms</em>.</p>\n<p>Is there terminology that would allow you to ask, “What <em>is</em> a cone?”, where I want to know the second case - that eliminating context, it <em>is</em> “a family of morphisms”. ?</p>",
        "id": 439442505,
        "sender_full_name": "Julius Hamilton",
        "timestamp": 1716128908
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure I quite understand the question, but a concise way to describe a cone is as a natural transformation (see <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/cone#in_category_theory\">here</a>  under 'Cones over a diagram').</p>",
        "id": 439445854,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathan Corbyn",
        "timestamp": 1716132170
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would say that this misses the idea that \"what something is\" should include not only the data needed to specify it, but also the data to distinguished it from another thing of the same kind. </p>\n<p>In this case, the family of arrows is sufficient to specify a cone, but different cones may share the same family of arrows (over different diagrams)</p>",
        "id": 439446860,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1716133183
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It’s not answering your question but there is a small ambiguity in asking “What is a cone?”. It could mean what is a cone in general or what is a cone in particular. By the second sense I think to “a” as it is used when you ask “How can someone know who is a person?”.</p>",
        "id": 439451805,
        "sender_full_name": "Jean-Baptiste Vienney",
        "timestamp": 1716138085
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Usually formal mathematics avoids any aspects of these questions that might become philosophically nontrivial; for instance, one might specify that \"a cone\" is a <em>triple</em> of a functor, an object, and a family of maps satisfying the cone condition, or one might say that \"a cone over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> with tip <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span>\" is the only concept that's being defined, without giving any notion of \"a cone\" at all. Interestingly, the latter gives \"cones\" as  a <em>dependent family</em> of sets, while the former gives \"cones\" as the <em>fibered family</em> formed by the \"sum type\" or \"Grothendieck construction' of the dependent family.</p>",
        "id": 439718684,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1716258997
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That sounds interesting.</p>\n<p>I was thinking that from the perspective of type theory, I basically mean the “top level type”, of a composite type. For example, a function from groups to integers is most fundamentally a function, not a group.</p>\n<p>Maybe there is a formal operation in type theory that is sort of like a forgetful functor where you can forget the details and focus on what the most definitive “type” of something is?</p>\n<p>In programming, the return type of a function is important information. It determines what you can do with the output, what methods can or cannot be called. That is what I think of as the “fundamental type”. When I say <em><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is a family of morphisms</em>, I cannot say, “What is the domain of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>?” A function has a domain. A family does not.</p>\n<p>So that’s the rough idea.</p>",
        "id": 439719917,
        "sender_full_name": "Julius Hamilton",
        "timestamp": 1716259631
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Type-theoretically, I'd say that a cone is a term of the type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>N</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Cone}(F,N)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Cone</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> for some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span>. You could then construct the type of all cones over functors <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>J</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">J\\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Σ</mi><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>N</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Sigma_{F,N}\\mathrm{Cone}(F,N)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0361em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Σ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">,</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Cone</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, and the type of <em>all</em> cones by a further $$\\Sigma$ over the domain and codomain on which the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> variable depends. Is this $$\\Sigma$ something like the \"forgetful\" operation you're looking for?</p>",
        "id": 439724787,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
